# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fluid-turbulence
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fluid-turbulence/direct-numerical-simulation] A **direct numerical simulation** (**DNS**) is a simulation in computational fluid dynamics (CFD) in which the Navier–Stokes equations are numerically solved without any turbulence model.
[src:fluid-turbulence/direct-numerical-simulation] This means that the whole range of spatial and temporal scales of the turbulence must be resolved.
[src:fluid-turbulence/direct-numerical-simulation] All the spatial scales of the turbulence must be resolved in the computational mesh, from the smallest dissipative scales (Kolmogorov microscales), up to the integral scale L , associated with the motions containing most of the kinetic energy.
[src:fluid-turbulence/direct-numerical-simulation] where $\nu$ is the kinematic viscosity and $\varepsilon$ is the rate of kinetic energy dissipation.
[src:fluid-turbulence/direct-numerical-simulation] On the other hand, the integral scale depends usually on the spatial scale of the boundary conditions.
[src:fluid-turbulence/direct-numerical-simulation] so that the Kolmogorov scale can be resolved.
[src:fluid-turbulence/direct-numerical-simulation] Hence, the memory storage requirement in a DNS grows very fast with the Reynolds number.
[src:fluid-turbulence/direct-numerical-simulation] In addition, given the very large memory necessary, the integration of the solution in time must be done by an explicit method.
[src:fluid-turbulence/direct-numerical-simulation] This means that in order to be accurate, the integration, for most discretization methods, must be done with a time step, $\Delta t$ , small enough such that a fluid particle moves only a fraction of the mesh spacing h in each step.
[src:fluid-turbulence/direct-numerical-simulation] Combining these relations, and the fact that h must be of the order of $\eta$ , the number of time-integration steps must be proportional to $L/(C\eta )$ .
[src:fluid-turbulence/direct-numerical-simulation] and consequently, the number of time steps grows also as a power law of the Reynolds number.
[src:fluid-turbulence/direct-numerical-simulation] One can estimate that the number of floating-point operations required to complete the simulation is proportional to the number of mesh points and the number of time steps, and in conclusion, the number of operations grows as $\mathrm {Re} ^{3}$ .
[src:fluid-turbulence/direct-numerical-simulation] Therefore, the computational cost of DNS is very high, even at low Reynolds numbers.
[src:fluid-turbulence/direct-numerical-simulation] For the Reynolds numbers encountered in most industrial applications, the computational resources required by a DNS would exceed the capacity of the most powerful computers currently available.
[src:fluid-turbulence/direct-numerical-simulation] However, direct numerical simulation is a useful tool in fundamental research in turbulence.
[src:fluid-turbulence/direct-numerical-simulation] Using DNS it is possible to perform "numerical experiments", and extract from them information difficult or impossible to obtain in the laboratory, allowing a better understanding of the physics of turbulence.
[src:fluid-turbulence/direct-numerical-simulation] Also, direct numerical simulations are useful in the development of turbulence models for practical applications, such as sub-grid scale models for large eddy simulation (LES) and models for methods that solve the Reynolds-averaged Navier–Stokes equations (RANS).
[src:fluid-turbulence/direct-numerical-simulation] This is done by means of "a priori" tests, in which the input data for the model is taken from a DNS simulation, or by "a posteriori" tests, in which the results produced by the model are compared with those obtained by DNS.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] In fluid dynamics, an **eddy** is the swirling of a fluid and the reverse current created when the fluid is in a turbulent flow regime.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] The moving fluid creates a space devoid of downstream-flowing fluid on the downstream side of the object.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] Fluid behind the obstacle flows into the void creating a swirl of fluid on each edge of the obstacle, followed by a short reverse flow of fluid behind the obstacle flowing upstream, toward the back of the obstacle.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] This phenomenon is naturally observed behind large emergent rocks in swift-flowing rivers.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] An eddy is a movement of fluid that deviates from the general flow of the fluid.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] An example for an eddy is a vortex which produces such deviation.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] However, there are other types of eddies that are not simple vortices.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] For example, a Rossby wave is an eddy which is an undulation that is a deviation from mean flow, but does not have the local closed streamlines of a vortex.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] The propensity of a fluid to swirl is used to promote good fuel/air mixing in internal combustion engines.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] In fluid mechanics and transport phenomena, an eddy is not a property of the fluid, but a violent swirling motion caused by the position and direction of turbulent flow.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] In 1883, scientist Osborne Reynolds conducted a fluid dynamics experiment involving water and dye, where he adjusted the velocities of the fluids and observed the transition from laminar to turbulent flow, characterized by the formation of eddies and vortices.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] Turbulent flow is defined as the flow in which the system's inertial forces are dominant over the viscous forces.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] This phenomenon is described by Reynolds number, a unit-less number used to determine when turbulent flow will occur.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] Conceptually, the Reynolds number is the ratio between inertial forces and viscous forces.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] where v is the velocity of the fluid, ρ is its density, r is the radius of the tube, and μ is the dynamic viscosity of the fluid.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] Note that that inclusion of ${\tfrac {2}{3}}\rho \kappa \delta _{i,j}$ in the linear constitutive relation is required by tensorial algebra purposes when solving for two-equation turbulence models (or any other turbulence model that solves a transport equation for $\kappa$ .
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] Hemodynamics is the study of blood flow in the circulatory system.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] Blood flow in straight sections of the arterial tree are typically laminar (high, directed wall stress), but branches and curvatures in the system cause turbulent flow.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] Turbulent flow in the arterial tree can cause a number of concerning effects, including atherosclerotic lesions, postsurgical neointimal hyperplasia, in-stent restenosis, vein bypass graft failure, transplant vasculopathy, and aortic valve calcification.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] Lift and drag properties of golf balls are customized by the manipulation of dimples along the surface of the ball, allowing for the golf ball to travel further and faster in the air.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] The data from turbulent-flow phenomena has been used to model different transitions in fluid flow regimes, which are used to thoroughly mix fluids and increase reaction rates within industrial processes.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] Oceanic and atmospheric currents transfer particles, debris, and organisms all across the globe.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] While the transport of organisms, such as phytoplankton, are essential for the preservation of ecosystems, oil and other pollutants are also mixed in the current flow and can carry pollution far from its origin.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] Eddy formations circulate trash and other pollutants into concentrated areas which researchers are tracking to improve clean-up and pollution prevention.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] The distribution and motion of plastics caused by eddy formations in natural water bodies can be predicted using Lagrangian transport models.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] Mesoscale ocean eddies play crucial roles in transferring heat poleward, as well as maintaining heat gradients at different depths.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] Modeling eddy development, as it relates to turbulence and fate transport phenomena, is vital in grasping an understanding of environmental systems.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] By understanding the transport of both particulate and dissolved solids in environmental flows, scientists and engineers will be able to efficiently formulate remediation strategies for pollution events.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] Eddy formations play a vital role in the fate and transport of solutes and particles in environmental flows such as in rivers, lakes, oceans, and the atmosphere.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] Upwelling in stratified coastal estuaries warrant the formation of dynamic eddies which distribute nutrients out from beneath the boundary layer to form plumes.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] Shallow waters, such as those along the coast, play a complex role in the transport of nutrients and pollutants due to the proximity of the upper-boundary driven by the wind and the lower-boundary near the bottom of the water body.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] Eddies are common in the ocean, and range in diameter from centimeters to hundreds of kilometers.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] The smallest scale eddies may last for a matter of seconds, while the larger features may persist for months to years.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] Eddies that are between about 10 and 500 km (6.2 and 310.7 mi) in diameter and persist for periods of days to months are known in oceanography as mesoscale eddies.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] Mesoscale eddies can be split into two categories: static eddies, caused by flow around an obstacle (see animation), and transient eddies, caused by baroclinic instability.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] When the ocean contains a sea surface height gradient, this creates a jet or current, such as the Antarctic Circumpolar Current.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] This current, as part of a baroclinically unstable system, meanders and creates eddies (in much the same way as a meandering river forms an oxbow lake).
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] These types of mesoscale eddies have been observed in many major ocean currents, including the Gulf Stream, the Agulhas Current, the Kuroshio Current, and the Antarctic Circumpolar Current, amongst others.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] Mesoscale ocean eddies are characterized by currents that flow in a roughly circular motion around the center of the eddy.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] The sense of rotation of these currents may either be cyclonic or anticyclonic (such as Haida Eddies).
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] Oceanic eddies are also usually made of water masses that are different from those outside the eddy.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] That is, the water within an eddy usually has different temperature and salinity characteristics to the water outside the eddy.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] There is a direct link between the water mass properties of an eddy and its rotation.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] Warm eddies rotate anti-cyclonically, while cold eddies rotate cyclonically.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] Because eddies may have a vigorous circulation associated with them, they are of concern to naval and commercial operations at sea.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] Further, because eddies transport anomalously warm or cold water as they move, they have an important influence on heat transport in certain parts of the ocean.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] The sub-tropical Northern Atlantic is known to have both cyclonic and anticyclonic eddies that are associated with high surface chlorophyll and low surface chlorophyll, respectively.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] The presence of chlorophyll and higher levels of chlorophyll allows this region to support higher biomass of phytoplankton, as well as, supported by areas of increased vertical nutrient fluxes and transportation of biological communities.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] This area of the Atlantic is also thought to be an ocean desert, which creates an interesting paradox due to it hosting a variety of large pelagic fish populations and apex predators.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] These mesoscale eddies have shown to be beneficial in further creating ecosystem-based management for food web models to better understand the utilization of these eddies by both the apex predators and their prey.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] (2018), used “Smart” Position or Temperature Transmitting tags (SPOT) and Pop-Up Satellite Archival Transmitting tags (PSAT) to track the movement and diving behavior of two female white sharks (Carcharodon carcharias) within the eddies.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] The eddies were defined using sea surface height (SSH) and contours using the horizontal speed-based radius scale.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] This study found that the white sharks dove in both cyclones but favored the anticyclone which had three times more dives as the cyclonic eddies.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] Additionally, in the Gulf Stream eddies, the anticyclonic eddies were 57% more common and had more dives and deeper dives than the open ocean eddies and Gulf Stream cyclonic eddies.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] Within these anticyclonic eddies, the isotherm was displaced 50 meters downward allowing for the warmer water to penetrate deeper in the water column.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] This warmer water displacement may allow for the white sharks to make longer dives without the added energetic cost from thermal regulation in the cooler cyclones.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] Even though these anticyclonic eddies resulted in lower levels of chlorophyll in comparison to the cyclonic eddies, the warmer waters at deeper depths may allow for a deeper mixed layer and higher concentration of diatoms which in turn result in higher rates of primary productivity.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] Furthermore, the prey populations could be distributed more within these eddies attracting these larger female sharks to forage in this mesopelagic zone.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] This diving pattern may follow a diel vertical migration but without more evidence on the biomass of their prey within this zone, these conclusions cannot be made only using this circumstantial evidence.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] The biomass in the mesopelagic zone is still understudied leading to the biomass of fish within this layer to potentially be underestimated.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] A more accurate measurement on this biomass may serve to benefit the commercial fishing industry providing them with additional fishing grounds within this region.
[src:fluid-turbulence/eddy-fluid-dynamics] Moreover, further understanding this region in the open ocean and how the removal of fish in this region may impact this pelagic food web is crucial for the fish populations and apex predators that may rely on this food source in addition to making better ecosystem-based management plans.
[src:fluid-turbulence/kolmogorov-microscales] In fluid dynamics, **Kolmogorov microscales** are the smallest scales in turbulent flow.
[src:fluid-turbulence/kolmogorov-microscales] At the Kolmogorov scale, viscosity dominates and the turbulence kinetic energy is dissipated into thermal energy.
[src:fluid-turbulence/kolmogorov-microscales] Typical values of the Kolmogorov length scale, for atmospheric motion in which the large eddies have length scales on the order of kilometers, range from 0.1 to 10 millimeters; for smaller flows such as in laboratory systems, η may be much smaller.
[src:fluid-turbulence/kolmogorov-microscales] In 1941, Andrey Kolmogorov introduced the hypothesis that the smallest scales of turbulence are universal (similar for every turbulent flow) and that they depend only on ε and ν.
[src:fluid-turbulence/kolmogorov-microscales] The definitions of the Kolmogorov microscales can be obtained using this idea and dimensional analysis.
[src:fluid-turbulence/kolmogorov-microscales] Since the dimension of kinematic viscosity is length2/time, and the dimension of the energy dissipation rate per unit mass is length2/time3, the only combination that has the dimension of time is $\tau _{\eta }={\sqrt {\tfrac {\nu }{\varepsilon }}}$ which is the Kolmogorov time scale.
[src:fluid-turbulence/kolmogorov-microscales] Similarly, the Kolmogorov length scale is the only combination of ε and ν that has dimension of length.
[src:fluid-turbulence/kolmogorov-microscales] Kolmogorov's 1941 theory is a mean field theory since it assumes that the relevant dynamical parameter is the mean energy dissipation rate.
[src:fluid-turbulence/kolmogorov-microscales] In fluid turbulence, the energy dissipation rate fluctuates in space and time, so it is possible to think of the microscales as quantities that also vary in space and time.
[src:fluid-turbulence/kolmogorov-microscales] However, standard practice is to use mean field values since they represent the typical values of the smallest scales in a given flow.
[src:fluid-turbulence/kolmogorov-microscales] In 1961, Kolomogorov published a refined version of the similarity hypotheses that accounts for the log-normal distribution of the dissipation rate.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] The simulation of turbulent flows by numerically solving the Navier–Stokes equations requires resolving a very wide range of time and length scales, all of which affect the flow field.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] Such a resolution can be achieved with direct numerical simulation (DNS), but DNS is computationally expensive, and its cost prohibits simulation of practical engineering systems with complex geometry or flow configurations, such as turbulent jets, pumps, vehicles, and landing gear.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] The principal idea behind LES is to reduce the computational cost by ignoring the smallest length scales, which are the most computationally expensive to resolve, via low-pass filtering of the Navier–Stokes equations.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] Such a low-pass filtering, which can be viewed as a time- and spatial-averaging, effectively removes small-scale information from the numerical solution.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] This information is not irrelevant, however, and its effect on the flow field must be modelled, a task which is an active area of research for problems in which small-scales can play an important role, such as near-wall flows, reacting flows, and multiphase flows.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] An LES filter can be applied to a spatial and temporal field $\phi ({\boldsymbol {x}},t)$ and perform a spatial filtering operation, a temporal filtering operation, or both.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] where G is the filter convolution kernel.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] The filter kernel G has an associated cutoff length scale $\Delta$ and cutoff time scale $\tau _{c}$ .
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] Scales smaller than these are eliminated from ${\overline {\phi }}$ .
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] It is important to note that the large eddy simulation filtering operation does not satisfy the properties of a Reynolds operator.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] The governing equations of LES are obtained by filtering the partial differential equations governing the flow field $\rho {\boldsymbol {u}}({\boldsymbol {x}},t)$ .
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] There are differences between the incompressible and compressible LES governing equations, which lead to the definition of a new filtering operation.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] where ${\bar {p}}$ is the filtered pressure field and ${\bar {S}}_{ij}$ is the rate-of-strain tensor evaluated using the filtered velocity.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] The nonlinear filtered advection term ${\overline {u_{i}u_{j}}}$ is the chief cause of difficulty in LES modeling.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] It requires knowledge of the unfiltered velocity field, which is unknown, so it must be modeled.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] The analysis that follows illustrates the difficulty caused by the nonlinearity, namely, that it causes interaction between large and small scales, preventing separation of scales.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] with the residual stress tensor $\tau _{ij}$ grouping all unclosed terms.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] Modeling the unclosed term $\tau _{ij}$ is the task of sub-grid scale (SGS) models.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] This is made challenging by the fact that the subgrid stress tensor $\tau _{ij}$ must account for interactions among all scales, including filtered scales with unfiltered scales.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] where $J_{\phi }$ is the diffusive flux of $\phi$ , and $q_{j}$ is the sub-filter flux for the scalar $\phi$ .
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] and can similarly be split up into contributions from interactions between various scales.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] This sub-filter flux also requires a sub-filter model.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] This equation models the changes in time of the filtered variables ${\bar {u}}_{i}$ .
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] Since the unfiltered variables $u_{i}$ are not known, it is impossible to directly calculate ${\overline {\frac {\partial u_{i}u_{j}}{\partial x_{j}}}}$ .
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] For the governing equations of compressible flow, each equation, starting with the conservation of mass, is filtered.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] which results in an additional sub-filter term.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] However, it is desirable to avoid having to model the sub-filter scales of the mass conservation equation.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] which, in the limit of incompressibility, becomes the normal filtering operation.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] This concept can then be extended to write the Favre-filtered momentum equation for compressible flow.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] and the term ${\frac {\partial }{\partial x_{j}}}\left({\overline {\sigma }}_{ij}-{\tilde {\sigma }}_{ij}\right)$ represents a sub-filter viscous contribution from evaluating the viscosity $\mu (T)$ using the Favre-filtered temperature ${\tilde {T}}$ .
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] By analogy, the Leonard decomposition may also be written for the residual stress tensor for a filtered triple product ${\overline {\rho \phi \psi }}$ .
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] The triple product can be rewritten using the Favre filtering operator as ${\overline {\rho }}{\widetilde {\phi \psi }}$ , which is an unclosed term (it requires knowledge of the fields $\phi$ and $\psi$ , when only the fields ${\tilde {\phi }}$ and ${\tilde {\psi }}$ are known).
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] It can be broken up in a manner analogous to ${\overline {u_{i}u_{j}}}$ above, which results in a sub-filter stress tensor ${\overline {\rho }}\left({\widetilde {\phi \psi }}-{\tilde {\phi }}{\tilde {\psi }}\right)$ .
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] In addition to the filtered mass and momentum equations, filtering the kinetic energy equation can provide additional insight.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] where $\epsilon _{f}=2\nu {\bar {S}}_{ij}{\bar {S}}_{ij}$ is the dissipation of kinetic energy of the filtered velocity field by viscous stress, and $\Pi =-\tau _{ij}^{r}{\bar {S}}_{ij}$ represents the sub-filter scale (SFS) dissipation of kinetic energy.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] The terms on the left-hand side represent transport, and the terms on the right-hand side are sink terms that dissipate kinetic energy.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] The $\Pi$ SFS dissipation term is of particular interest, since it represents the transfer of energy from large resolved scales to small unresolved scales.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] On average, $\Pi$ transfers energy from large to small scales.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] However, instantaneously $\Pi$ can be positive *or* negative, meaning it can also act as a source term for $E_{f}$ , the kinetic energy of the filtered velocity field.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] The transfer of energy from unresolved to resolved scales is called **backscatter** (and likewise the transfer of energy from resolved to unresolved scales is called **forward-scatter**).
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] Large eddy simulation involves the solution to the discrete filtered governing equations using computational fluid dynamics.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] LES resolves scales from the domain size L down to the filter size $\Delta$ , and as such a substantial portion of high wave number turbulent fluctuations must be resolved.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] This requires either high-order numerical schemes, or fine grid resolution if low-order numerical schemes are used.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] Chapter 13 of Pope addresses the question of how fine a grid resolution $\Delta x$ is needed to resolve a filtered velocity field ${\overline {u}}({\boldsymbol {x}})$ .
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] Ghosal found that for low-order discretization schemes, such as those used in finite volume methods, the truncation error can be the same order as the subfilter scale contributions, unless the filter width $\Delta$ is considerably larger than the grid spacing $\Delta x$ .
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] While even-order schemes have truncation error, they are non-dissipative, and because subfilter scale models are dissipative, even-order schemes will not affect the subfilter scale model contributions as strongly as dissipative schemes.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] The filtering operation in large eddy simulation can be implicit or explicit.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] Implicit filtering recognizes that the subfilter scale model will dissipate in the same manner as many numerical schemes.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] In this way, the grid, or the numerical discretization scheme, can be assumed to be the LES low-pass filter.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] While this takes full advantage of the grid resolution, and eliminates the computational cost of calculating a subfilter scale model term, it is difficult to determine the shape of the LES filter that is associated with some numerical issues.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] Additionally, truncation error can also become an issue.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] In explicit filtering, an LES filter is applied to the discretized Navier–Stokes equations, providing a well-defined filter shape and reducing the truncation error.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] However, explicit filtering requires a finer grid than implicit filtering, and the computational cost increases with $(\Delta x)^{4}$ .
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] Chapter 8 of Sagaut (2006) covers LES numerics in greater detail.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] Inlet boundary conditions affect the accuracy of LES significantly, and the treatment of inlet conditions for LES is a complicated problem.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] (3) being easy to implement and adjust to different cases.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] The first method for generating turbulent inlets is to synthesize them according to particular cases, such as Fourier techniques, principle orthogonal decomposition (POD) and vortex methods.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] The synthesis techniques attempt to construct turbulent field at inlets that have suitable turbulence-like properties and make it easy to specify parameters of the turbulence, such as turbulent kinetic energy and turbulent dissipation rate.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] In addition, inlet conditions generated by using random numbers are computationally inexpensive.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] However, one serious drawback exists in the method.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] The synthesized turbulence does not satisfy the physical structure of fluid flow governed by Navier-Stokes equations.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] The second method involves a separate and precursor calculation to generate a turbulent database which can be introduced into the main computation at the inlets.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] The database (sometimes named as ‘library’) can be generated in a number of ways, such as cyclic domains, pre-prepared library, and internal mapping.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] However, the method of generating turbulent inflow by precursor simulations requires large calculation capacity.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] Researchers examining the application of various types of synthetic and precursor calculations have found that the more realistic the inlet turbulence, the more accurate LES predicts results.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] To discuss the modeling of unresolved scales, first the unresolved scales must be classified.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] They fall into two groups: **resolved sub-filter scales** (SFS), and **sub-grid scales**(SGS).
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] The resolved sub-filter scales represent the scales with wave numbers larger than the cutoff wave number $k_{c}$ , but whose effects are dampened by the filter.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] Resolved sub-filter scales only exist when filters non-local in wave-space are used (such as a box or Gaussian filter).
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] These resolved sub-filter scales must be modeled using filter reconstruction.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] Sub-grid scales are any scales that are smaller than the cutoff filter width $\Delta$ .
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] The form of the SGS model depends on the filter implementation.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] As mentioned in the Numerical methods for LES section, if implicit LES is considered, no SGS model is implemented and the numerical effects of the discretization are assumed to mimic the physics of the unresolved turbulent motions.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] Without a universally valid description of turbulence, empirical information must be utilized when constructing and applying SGS models, supplemented with fundamental physical constraints such as Galilean invariance .
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] Two classes of SGS models exist; the first class is **functional models** and the second class is **structural models**.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] Functional models are simpler than structural models, focusing only on dissipating energy at a rate that is physically correct.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] These are based on an artificial eddy viscosity approach, where the effects of turbulence are lumped into a turbulent viscosity.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] The approach treats dissipation of kinetic energy at sub-grid scales as analogous to molecular diffusion.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] Based on dimensional analysis, the eddy viscosity must have units of $\left[\nu _{\mathrm {t} }\right]={\frac {\mathrm {m^{2}} }{\mathrm {s} }}$ .
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] Most eddy viscosity SGS models model the eddy viscosity as the product of a characteristic length scale and a characteristic velocity scale.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] The first SGS model developed was the Smagorinsky–Lilly SGS model, which was developed by Smagorinsky and used in the first LES simulation by Deardorff.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] where $\Delta$ is the grid size and C is a constant.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] This method assumes that the energy production and dissipation of the small scales are in equilibrium - that is, $\epsilon =\Pi$ .
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] Germano et al. identified a number of studies using the Smagorinsky model that each found different values for the Smagorinsky constant C for different flow configurations.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] In an attempt to formulate a more universal approach to SGS models, Germano et al. proposed a dynamic Smagorinsky model, which utilized two filters: a grid LES filter, denoted ${\overline {f}}$ , and a test LES filter, denoted ${\hat {f}}$ for any turbulent field f .
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] The test filter is larger in size than the grid filter and adds an additional smoothing of the turbulence field over the already smoothed fields represented by the LES.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] Germano *et* al. noted that even though neither $\tau _{ij}$ nor $T_{ij}$ can be computed exactly because of the presence of unresolved scales, there is an exact relation connecting these two tensors.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] In order to do this, two additional steps were introduced in the original formulation.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] First, one assumed that even though C was in principle variable, the variation was sufficiently slow that it can be moved out of the filtering operation ${\widehat {C(.)}}=C{\widehat {(.)}}$ .
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] Second, since C was a scalar, the Germano identity was contracted with a second rank tensor (the rate of strain tensor was chosen) to convert it to a scalar equation from which C could be determined.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] Lilly found a less arbitrary and therefore more satisfactory approach for obtaining C from the tensor identity.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] He noted that the Germano identity required the satisfaction of nine equations at each point in space (of which only five are independent) for a single quantity C .
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] The problem of obtaining C was therefore over-determined.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] He proposed therefore that C be determined using a least square fit by minimizing the residuals.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] First, the computed coefficient was not at all "slowly varying" as assumed and varied as much as any other turbulent field.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] Secondly, the computed C could be positive as well as negative.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] A slight preponderance of positive values as opposed to strict positivity of the eddy-viscosity results in the observed net dissipation.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] This so-called "backscatter" of energy from small to large scales indeed corresponds to negative C values in the Smagorinsky model.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] Nevertheless, the Germano-Lilly formulation was found not to result in stable calculations.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] When the averaging involved a large enough statistical sample that the computed C was positive (or at least only rarely negative) stable calculations were possible.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] Simply setting the negative values to zero (a procedure called "clipping") with or without the averaging also resulted in stable calculations.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] Meneveau proposed an averaging over Lagrangian fluid trajectories with an exponentially decaying "memory".
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] This can be applied to problems lacking homogeneous directions and can be stable if the effective time over which the averaging is done is long enough and yet not so long as to smooth out spatial inhomogenieties of interest.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] Lilly's modification of the Germano method followed by a statistical averaging or synthetic removal of negative viscosity regions seems ad hoc, even if it could be made to "work".
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] An alternate formulation of the least square minimization procedure known as the "Dynamic Localization Model" (DLM) was suggested by Ghosal et al.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] with the tensors $\tau _{ij}$ and $T_{ij}$ replaced by the appropriate SGS model.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] This tensor then represents the amount by which the subgrid model fails to respect the Germano identity at each spatial location.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] making $E_{ij}$ an algebraic function of C which is then determined by requiring that $E_{ij}E_{ij}$ considered as a function of C have the least possible value.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] However, since the C thus obtained turns out to be just as variable as any other fluctuating quantity in turbulence, the original assumption of the constancy of C cannot be justified a posteriori.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] In the DLM approach one avoids this inconsistency by not invoking the step of removing C from the test filtering operation.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] where the integral ranges over the whole fluid volume.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] This global error $E[C(x,y,z,t)]$ is then a functional of the spatially varying function $C(x,y,z,t)$ (here the time instant, t , is fixed and therefore appears just as a parameter) which is determined so as to minimize this functional.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] where the functions $K({\boldsymbol {x}},{\boldsymbol {y}})$ and $f({\boldsymbol {x}})$ are defined in terms of the resolved fields $L_{ij},\alpha _{ij},\beta _{ij}$ and are therefore known at each time step and the integral ranges over the whole fluid domain.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] The integral equation is solved numerically by an iteration procedure and convergence was found to be generally rapid if used with a pre-conditioning scheme.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] Even though this variational approach removes an inherent inconsistency in Lilly's approach, the $C(x,y,z,t)$ obtained from the integral equation still displayed the instability associated with negative viscosities.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] This can be resolved by insisting that $E[C]$ be minimized subject to the constraint $C(x,y,z,t)\geq 0$ .
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] Here the suffix + indicates the "positive part of" that is, $x_{+}=(x+|x|)/2$ .
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] Even though this superficially looks like "clipping" it is not an ad hoc scheme but a bonafide solution of the constrained variational problem.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] This DLM(+) model was found to be stable and yielded excellent results for forced and decaying isotropic turbulence, channel flows and a variety of other more complex geometries.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] If a flow happens to have homogeneous directions (let us say the directions x and z) then one can introduce the ansatz $C=C(y,t)$ .
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] The variational approach then immediately yields Lilly's result with averaging over homogeneous directions without any need for ad hoc modifications of a prior result.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] One shortcoming of the DLM(+) model was that it did not describe backscatter which is known to be a real "thing" from analyzing DNS data.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] Two approaches were developed to address this.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] In one approach due to Carati et al. a fluctuating force with amplitude determined by the fluctuation-dissipation theorem is added in analogy to Landau's theory of fluctuating hydrodynamics.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] In the second approach, one notes that any "backscattered" energy appears in the resolved scales only at the expense of energy in the subgrid scales.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] The DLM can be modified in a simple way to take into account this physical fact so as to allow for backscatter while being inherently stable.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] This k-equation version of the DLM, DLM(k) replaces $\Delta |{\bar {S}}|$ in the Smagorinsky eddy viscosity model by ${\sqrt {k}}$ as an appropriate velocity scale.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] where $\nu$ is the kinematic viscosity and $C_{*},D$ are positive coefficients representing kinetic energy dissipation and diffusion respectively.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] These can be determined following the dynamic procedure with constrained minimization as in DLM(+).
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] This approach, though more expensive to implement than the DLM(+) was found to be stable and resulted in good agreement with experimental data for a variety of flows tested.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] Furthermore, it is mathematically impossible for the DLM(k) to result in an unstable computation as the sum of the large scale and SGS energies is non-increasing by construction.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] Both of these approaches incorporating backscatter works well.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] They yield models that are slightly less dissipative with somewhat improved performance over the DLM(+).
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] The DLM(k) model additionally yields the subgrid kinetic energy, which may be a physical quantity of interest.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] These improvements are achieved at a somewhat increased cost in model implementation.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] The Dynamic Model originated at the 1990 Summer Program of the Center for Turbulence Research (CTR) at Stanford University.
[src:fluid-turbulence/large-eddy-simulation] A series of "CTR-Tea" seminars celebrated the 30th Anniversary Archived 2022-10-30 at the Wayback Machine of this important milestone in turbulence modeling.
[src:fluid-turbulence/reynolds-averaged-navier-stokes-equations] The **Reynolds-averaged Navier–Stokes equations** (**RANS equations**) are time-averaged equations of motion for fluid flow.
[src:fluid-turbulence/reynolds-averaged-navier-stokes-equations] The idea behind the equations is Reynolds decomposition, whereby an instantaneous quantity is decomposed into its time-averaged and fluctuating quantities, an idea first proposed by Osborne Reynolds.
[src:fluid-turbulence/reynolds-averaged-navier-stokes-equations] The RANS equations are primarily used to describe turbulent flows.
[src:fluid-turbulence/reynolds-averaged-navier-stokes-equations] These equations can be used with approximations based on knowledge of the properties of flow turbulence to give approximate time-averaged solutions to the Navier–Stokes equations.
[src:fluid-turbulence/reynolds-averaged-navier-stokes-equations] The left hand side of this equation represents the change in mean momentum of a fluid element owing to the unsteadiness in the mean flow and the convection by the mean flow.
[src:fluid-turbulence/reynolds-averaged-navier-stokes-equations] This change is balanced by the mean body force, the isotropic stress owing to the mean pressure field, the viscous stresses, and apparent stress $\left(-\rho {\overline {u_{i}^{\prime }u_{j}^{\prime }}}\right)$ owing to the fluctuating velocity field, generally referred to as the Reynolds stress.
[src:fluid-turbulence/reynolds-averaged-navier-stokes-equations] This nonlinear Reynolds stress term requires additional modeling to close the RANS equation for solving, and has led to the creation of many different turbulence models.
[src:fluid-turbulence/reynolds-averaged-navier-stokes-equations] The time-average operator ${\overline {.}}$ is a Reynolds operator.
[src:fluid-turbulence/reynolds-averaged-navier-stokes-equations] The basic tool required for the derivation of the RANS equations from the instantaneous Navier–Stokes equations is the Reynolds decomposition.
[src:fluid-turbulence/reynolds-averaged-navier-stokes-equations] Reynolds decomposition refers to separation of the flow variable (like velocity u ) into the mean (time-averaged) component ( ${\overline {u}}$ ) and the fluctuating component ( $u^{\prime }$ ).
[src:fluid-turbulence/reynolds-averaged-navier-stokes-equations] Because the mean operator is a Reynolds operator, it has a set of properties.
[src:fluid-turbulence/reynolds-averaged-navier-stokes-equations] One of these properties is that the mean of the fluctuating quantity is equal to zero $({\bar {u'}})$ Some authors prefer using U instead of ${\bar {u}}$ for the mean term (since an overbar is sometimes used to represent a vector).
[src:fluid-turbulence/reynolds-averaged-navier-stokes-equations] In this case, the fluctuating term $u^{\prime }$ is represented instead by u .
[src:fluid-turbulence/reynolds-averaged-navier-stokes-equations] This is possible because the two terms do not appear simultaneously in the same equation.
[src:fluid-turbulence/reynolds-averaged-navier-stokes-equations] To avoid confusion, the notation u , ${\bar {u}}$ , and $u'$ will be used to represent the instantaneous, mean, and fluctuating terms, respectively.
[src:fluid-turbulence/reynolds-averaged-navier-stokes-equations] The properties of Reynolds operators are useful in the derivation of the RANS equations.
[src:fluid-turbulence/reynolds-averaged-navier-stokes-equations] If ${\overline {u_{i}^{\prime }u_{j}^{\prime }}}$ is traced, turbulence kinetic energy is obtained.
[src:fluid-turbulence/reynolds-averaged-navier-stokes-equations] All RANS models are based on the above equation.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence-modeling] In fluid dynamics, **turbulence modeling** is the construction and use of a mathematical model to predict the effects of turbulence.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence-modeling] Turbulent flows are commonplace in most real-life scenarios.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence-modeling] In spite of decades of research, there is no analytical theory to predict the evolution of these turbulent flows.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence-modeling] The equations governing turbulent flows can only be solved directly for simple cases of flow.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence-modeling] For most real-life turbulent flows, CFD simulations use turbulent models to predict the evolution of turbulence.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence-modeling] These turbulence models are simplified constitutive equations that predict the statistical evolution of turbulent flows.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence-modeling] The Navier–Stokes equations govern the velocity and pressure of a fluid flow.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence-modeling] In a turbulent flow, each of these quantities may be decomposed into a mean part and a fluctuating part.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence-modeling] Averaging the equations gives the Reynolds-averaged Navier–Stokes (RANS) equations, which govern the mean flow.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence-modeling] However, the nonlinearity of the Navier–Stokes equations means that the velocity fluctuations still appear in the RANS equations, in the nonlinear term $-\rho {\overline {v_{i}^{\prime }v_{j}^{\prime }}}$ from the convective acceleration.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence-modeling] This term is known as the Reynolds stress, $R_{ij}$ .
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence-modeling] Its effect on the mean flow is like that of a stress term, such as from pressure or viscosity.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence-modeling] To obtain equations containing only the mean velocity and pressure, we need to close the RANS equations by modelling the Reynolds stress term $R_{ij}$ as a function of the mean flow, removing any reference to the fluctuating part of the velocity.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence-modeling] Joseph Valentin Boussinesq was the first to attack the closure problem, by introducing the concept of eddy viscosity.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence-modeling] In 1877 Boussinesq proposed relating the turbulence stresses to the mean flow to close the system of equations.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence-modeling] Here the Boussinesq hypothesis is applied to model the Reynolds stress term.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence-modeling] Note that a new proportionality constant $\nu _{t}>0$ , the *(kinematic) turbulence eddy viscosity*, has been introduced.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence-modeling] Models of this type are known as eddy viscosity models (EVMs).
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence-modeling] In this model, the additional turbulence stresses are given by augmenting the molecular viscosity with an eddy viscosity.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence-modeling] This can be a simple constant eddy viscosity (which works well for some free shear flows such as axisymmetric jets, 2-D jets, and mixing layers).
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence-modeling] It has since been found to be significantly less accurate than most practitioners would assume.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence-modeling] Still, turbulence models which employ the Boussinesq hypothesis have demonstrated significant practical value.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence-modeling] In cases with well-defined shear layers, this is likely due the dominance of streamwise shear components, so that considerable *relative* errors in flow-normal components are still negligible in *absolute* terms.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence-modeling] Beyond this, most eddy viscosity turbulence models contain coefficients which are calibrated against measurements, and thus produce reasonably accurate overall outcomes for flow fields of similar type as used for calibration.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence-modeling] Later, Ludwig Prandtl introduced the additional concept of the mixing length, along with the idea of a boundary layer.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence-modeling] For wall-bounded turbulent flows, the eddy viscosity must vary with distance from the wall, hence the addition of the concept of a 'mixing length'.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence-modeling] This simple model is the basis for the "law of the wall", which is a surprisingly accurate model for wall-bounded, attached (not separated) flow fields with small pressure gradients.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence-modeling] More general turbulence models have evolved over time, with most modern turbulence models given by field equations similar to the Navier–Stokes equations.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence-modeling] In the context of Large Eddy Simulation, turbulence modeling refers to the need to parameterize the subgrid scale stress in terms of features of the filtered velocity field.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence-modeling] This field is called subgrid-scale modeling.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence-modeling] The Boussinesq hypothesis is employed in the Spalart–Allmaras (S–A), *k*–ε (*k*–epsilon), and *k*–ω (*k*–omega) models and offers a relatively low cost computation for the turbulence viscosity $\nu _{t}$ .
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence-modeling] The S–A model uses only one additional equation to model turbulence viscosity transport, while the *k*–ε and *k*–ω models use two.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence-modeling] The following is a brief overview of commonly employed models in modern engineering applications.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] In fluid dynamics, **turbulence** or **turbulent flow** is fluid motion exhibiting chaotic changes in pressure and flow velocity.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] It is in contrast to *laminar flow*, which occurs when a fluid flows in parallel layers with no disruption between those layers.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] Turbulence is commonly observed in everyday phenomena such as surf, fast flowing rivers, billowing storm clouds, or smoke from a chimney, and most fluid flows occurring in nature or created in engineering applications are turbulent.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] Turbulence is caused by excessive kinetic energy in parts of a fluid flow, which overcomes the damping effect of the fluid's viscosity.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] For this reason, turbulence is commonly realized in low viscosity fluids.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] In general terms, in turbulent flow, unsteady vortices appear of many sizes which interact with each other, consequently drag due to friction effects increases.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] The onset of turbulence can be predicted by the dimensionless Reynolds number, the ratio of kinetic energy to viscous damping in a fluid flow.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] However, turbulence has long resisted detailed physical analysis, and the interactions within turbulence create a very complex phenomenon.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] Physicist Richard Feynman described turbulence as the most important unsolved problem in classical physics.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] The turbulence intensity affects many fields, for examples fish ecology, air pollution, precipitation, and climate change.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] Is it possible to make a theoretical model to describe the behavior of a turbulent flow—in particular, its internal structures?
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] Turbulent flows are always highly irregular.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] For this reason, turbulence problems are normally treated statistically rather than deterministically.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] However, not all chaotic flows are turbulent.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] The readily available supply of energy in turbulent flows tends to accelerate the homogenization (mixing) of fluid mixtures.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] The characteristic which is responsible for the enhanced mixing and increased rates of mass, momentum and energy transports in a flow is called "diffusivity".
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] This turbulent diffusion coefficient is defined in a phenomenological sense, by analogy with the molecular diffusivities, but it does not have a true physical meaning, being dependent on the flow conditions, and not a property of the fluid itself.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] and the gradient of a mean variable similar to the relation between flux and gradient that exists for molecular transport.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] In the best case, this assumption is only an approximation.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] Nevertheless, the turbulent diffusivity is the simplest approach for quantitative analysis of turbulent flows, and many models have been postulated to calculate it.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] In rivers and large ocean currents, the diffusion coefficient is given by variations of Elder's formula.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] In fluid dynamics, they are essentially vortices subjected to stretching associated with a corresponding increase of the component of vorticity in the stretching direction—due to the conservation of angular momentum.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] On the other hand, vortex stretching is the core mechanism on which the turbulence energy cascade relies to establish and maintain identifiable structure function.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] In general, the stretching mechanism implies thinning of the vortices in the direction perpendicular to the stretching direction due to volume conservation of fluid elements.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] As a result, the radial length scale of the vortices decreases and the larger flow structures break down into smaller structures.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] The process continues until the small scale structures are small enough that their kinetic energy can be transformed by the fluid's molecular viscosity into heat.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] Turbulent flow is always rotational and three dimensional.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] For example, atmospheric cyclones are rotational but their substantially two-dimensional shapes do not allow vortex generation and so are not turbulent.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] On the other hand, oceanic flows are dispersive but essentially non rotational and therefore are not turbulent.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] To sustain turbulent flow, a persistent source of energy supply is required because turbulence dissipates rapidly as the kinetic energy is converted into internal energy by viscous shear stress.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] Most of the kinetic energy of the turbulent motion is contained in the large-scale structures.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] This process continues, creating smaller and smaller structures which produces a hierarchy of eddies.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] Eventually this process creates structures that are small enough that molecular diffusion becomes important and viscous dissipation of energy finally takes place.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] The eddies are loosely defined as coherent patterns of flow velocity, vorticity and pressure.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] The scales in the energy cascade are generally uncontrollable and highly non-symmetric.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] Nevertheless, based on these length scales these eddies can be divided into three categories.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] Large eddies obtain energy from the mean flow and also from each other.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] Thus, these are the energy production eddies which contain most of the energy.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] They have the large flow velocity fluctuation and are low in frequency.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] and are defined in terms of the normalized two-point flow velocity correlations.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] The maximum length of these scales is constrained by the characteristic length of the apparatus.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] For example, the largest integral length scale of pipe flow is equal to the pipe diameter.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] ′ is the velocity fluctuation in that same direction.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] Smallest scales in the spectrum that form the viscous sub-layer range.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] In this range, the energy input from nonlinear interactions and the energy drain from viscous dissipation are in exact balance.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] The intermediate scales between the largest and the smallest scales which make the inertial subrange.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] Taylor microscales are not dissipative scales, but pass down the energy from the largest to the smallest without dissipation.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] Some literatures do not consider Taylor microscales as a characteristic length scale and consider the energy cascade to contain only the largest and smallest scales; while the latter accommodate both the inertial subrange and the viscous sublayer.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] Nevertheless, Taylor microscales are often used in describing the term "turbulence" more conveniently as these Taylor microscales play a dominant role in energy and momentum transfer in the wavenumber space.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] Although it is possible to find some particular solutions of the Navier–Stokes equations governing fluid motion, all such solutions are unstable to finite perturbations at large Reynolds numbers.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] Sensitive dependence on the initial and boundary conditions makes fluid flow irregular both in time and in space so that a statistical description is needed.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] The Russian mathematician Andrey Kolmogorov proposed the first statistical theory of turbulence, based on the aforementioned notion of the energy cascade (an idea originally introduced by Richardson) and the concept of self-similarity.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] As a result, the Kolmogorov microscales were named after him.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] It is now known that the self-similarity is broken so the statistical description is presently modified.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] A complete description of turbulence is one of the unsolved problems in physics.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] According to an apocryphal story, Werner Heisenberg was asked what he would ask God, given the opportunity.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] His reply was: "When I meet God, I am going to ask him two questions: Why relativity?
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] I really believe he will have an answer for the first." A similar witticism has been attributed to Horace Lamb in a speech to the British Association for the Advancement of Science: "I am an old man now, and when I die and go to heaven there are two matters on which I hope for enlightenment.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] One is quantum electrodynamics, and the other is the turbulent motion of fluids.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] A similar effect is created by the introduction of a stream of higher velocity fluid, such as the hot gases from a flame in air.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] This relative movement generates fluid friction, which is a factor in developing turbulent flow.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] Counteracting this effect is the viscosity of the fluid, which as it increases, progressively inhibits turbulence, as more kinetic energy is absorbed by a more viscous fluid.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] The Reynolds number quantifies the relative importance of these two types of forces for given flow conditions, and is a guide to when turbulent flow will occur in a particular situation.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] Such scaling is not always linear and the application of Reynolds numbers to both situations allows scaling factors to be developed.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] A flow situation in which the kinetic energy is significantly absorbed due to the action of fluid molecular viscosity gives rise to a laminar flow regime.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] For this the dimensionless quantity the Reynolds number (Re) is used as a guide.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] While there is no theorem directly relating the non-dimensional Reynolds number to turbulence, flows at Reynolds numbers larger than 5000 are typically (but not necessarily) turbulent, while those at low Reynolds numbers usually remain laminar.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] In Poiseuille flow, for example, turbulence can first be sustained if the Reynolds number is larger than a critical value of about 2040; moreover, the turbulence is generally interspersed with laminar flow until a larger Reynolds number of about 4000.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] The transition occurs if the size of the object is gradually increased, or the viscosity of the fluid is decreased, or if the density of the fluid is increased.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] When flow is turbulent, particles exhibit additional transverse motion which enhances the rate of energy and momentum exchange between them, thus increasing the heat transfer and the friction coefficient.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] Assume for a two-dimensional turbulent flow that one was able to locate a specific point in the fluid and measure the actual flow velocity **v** = (*vx*,*vy*) of every particle that passed through that point at any given time.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] and similarly for temperature (*T* = *T* + *T′*) and pressure (*P* = *P* + *P′*), where the primed quantities denote fluctuations superposed to the mean.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] This decomposition of a flow variable into a mean value and a turbulent fluctuation was originally proposed by Osborne Reynolds in 1895, and is considered to be the beginning of the systematic mathematical analysis of turbulent flow, as a sub-field of fluid dynamics.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] While the mean values are taken as predictable variables determined by dynamics laws, the turbulent fluctuations are regarded as stochastic variables.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] where cP is the heat capacity at constant pressure, ρ is the density of the fluid, *μ*turb is the coefficient of turbulent viscosity and *k*turb is the turbulent thermal conductivity.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] Richardson's notion of turbulence was that a turbulent flow is composed by "eddies" of different sizes.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] The sizes define a characteristic length scale for the eddies, which are also characterized by flow velocity scales and time scales (turnover time) dependent on the length scale.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] The large eddies are unstable and eventually break up originating smaller eddies, and the kinetic energy of the initial large eddy is divided into the smaller eddies that stemmed from it.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] These smaller eddies undergo the same process, giving rise to even smaller eddies which inherit the energy of their predecessor eddy, and so on.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] In this way, the energy is passed down from the large scales of the motion to smaller scales until reaching a sufficiently small length scale such that the viscosity of the fluid can effectively dissipate the kinetic energy into internal energy.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] In his original theory of 1941, Kolmogorov postulated that for very high Reynolds numbers, the small-scale turbulent motions are statistically isotropic (i.e. no preferential spatial direction could be discerned).
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] In general, the large scales of a flow are not isotropic, since they are determined by the particular geometrical features of the boundaries (the size characterizing the large scales will be denoted as L).
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] Thus, Kolmogorov introduced a second hypothesis: for very high Reynolds numbers the statistics of small scales are universally and uniquely determined by the kinematic viscosity ν and the rate of energy dissipation ε.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] This is today known as the Kolmogorov length scale (see Kolmogorov microscales).
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] A turbulent flow is characterized by a hierarchy of scales through which the energy cascade takes place.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] Dissipation of kinetic energy takes place at scales of the order of Kolmogorov length η, while the input of energy into the cascade comes from the decay of the large scales, of order L.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] These two scales at the extremes of the cascade can differ by several orders of magnitude at high Reynolds numbers.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] In between there is a range of scales (each one with its own characteristic length r) that has formed at the expense of the energy of the large ones.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] These scales are very large compared with the Kolmogorov length, but still very small compared with the large scale of the flow (i.e.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] Within this range inertial effects are still much larger than viscous effects, and it is possible to assume that viscosity does not play a role in their internal dynamics (for this reason this range is called "inertial range").
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] Hence, a third hypothesis of Kolmogorov was that at very high Reynolds number the statistics of scales in the range *η* ≪ *r* ≪ *L* are universally and uniquely determined by the scale r and the rate of energy dissipation ε.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] The way in which the kinetic energy is distributed over the multiplicity of scales is a fundamental characterization of a turbulent flow.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] where **û**(**k**) is the Fourier transform of the flow velocity field.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] where ⁠1/2⁠⟨*uiui*⟩ is the mean turbulent kinetic energy of the flow.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] The wavenumber k corresponding to length scale r is *k* = ⁠2π/*r*⁠.
