[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] This is one of the most famous results of Kolmogorov 1941 theory, describing transport of energy through scale space without any loss or gain.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] The Kolmogorov five-thirds law was first observed in a tidal channel, and considerable experimental evidence has since accumulated that supports it.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] In spite of this success, Kolmogorov theory is at present under revision.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] This theory implicitly assumes that the turbulence is statistically self-similar at different scales.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] This essentially means that the statistics are scale-invariant and non-intermittent in the inertial range.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] that is, the difference in flow velocity between points separated by a vector **r** (since the turbulence is assumed isotropic, the flow velocity increment depends only on the modulus of **r**).
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] Flow velocity increments are useful because they emphasize the effects of scales of the order of the separation r when statistics are computed.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] where the brackets denote the statistical average, and the Cn would be universal constants.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] There is considerable evidence that turbulent flows deviate from this behavior.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] The scaling exponents deviate from the ⁠*n*/3⁠ value predicted by the theory, becoming a non-linear function of the order n of the structure function.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] The universality of the constants have also been questioned.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] For low orders the discrepancy with the Kolmogorov ⁠*n*/3⁠ value is very small, which explain the success of Kolmogorov theory in regards to low order statistical moments.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] Since the experimental values obtained for the second order structure function only deviate slightly from the ⁠2/3⁠ value predicted by Kolmogorov theory, the value for p is very near to ⁠5/3⁠ (differences are about 2%).
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] Thus the "Kolmogorov −⁠5/3⁠ spectrum" is generally observed in turbulence.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] However, for high order structure functions, the difference with the Kolmogorov scaling is significant, and the breakdown of the statistical self-similarity is clear.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] This behavior, and the lack of universality of the Cn constants, are related with the phenomenon of intermittency in turbulence and can be related to the non-trivial scaling behavior of the dissipation rate averaged over scale r.
[src:fluid-turbulence/turbulence] This is an important area of research in this field, and a major goal of the modern theory of turbulence is to understand what is universal in the inertial range, and how to deduce intermittency properties from the Navier-Stokes equations, i.e. from first principles.
